Title: Whychus Restoration
Description: This video details our our work on Whychus Creek.  We learned a lot and had even more fun!  Replanting native willows, dogwood, and spirea, we brought Whychus a little closer to the healthy stream we all know it can be!

Title: Caddisfly casing movement
Description: Two empty casing made of pebbles, one with sticks that is alive and moving.

Title: Restoration Time Lapse 2010
Description: This time-lapse video details a restoration project on the Salmon River to increase in-stream habitat through the addition of large wood.  Over time, the stream will increase in complexity, accruing additional wood, creating new pools, hydrologic variation, and spawning gravels.

Title: DESCHUTES CHILDRENS FOREST - Be a part of it!
Description: The Upper Deschutes Watershed Council coordinates place-based education opportunities to help local students reconnect to the natural world. Providing hands-on education projects, the Watershed Council guides local students to forge a lifelong, caretaking bond with their local watershed. By helping students develop a sense of self while they also develop a sense of environmental stewardship, the Watershed Council seeks to ensure the health of Oregon's rivers and streams for generations.

Title: Wallowa County Schools Fall 2011 Water Quality Results
Description: This video shows students from Wallowa, Enterprise, and Joseph Schools sharing their results from Stream Shape, Macroinvertebrates, Water Chemistry, and Riparian Vegetation Teams.

Title: Master Watershed Stewards
Description: After the Coos Bay School District went to a four day school week, the Coos Watershed Association worked with Oregon State University Extension Service and regional partners to come up with a Friday program that would fulfill education credits for students, provide career training in watershed science and forestry, and promote stewardship in the Coos watershed.
